<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-354-824  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 354 824.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  April 9 1990 v4 n14 p14(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New FAR rules focus buying procedures, penalties. (FederalAcquisition Regulation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gallatin, James P. Jr.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Congress plans to adopt stringent and extensive requirementsconcerning the behavior of contractor and government personnelduring federal procurements.andP;  These requirements are contained ina new 'Procurement Integrity' section of the Federal AcquisitionRegulation (FAR).andP;  They include training programs to ensure thataffected personnel are aware of the new requirements, prohibitionsagainst discussing employment or business opportunities withprocurement officials, and certifications that such discussionshave not occurred.andP;  There are harsh penalties for noncompliance,and further FAR amendments are anticipated.andP;  Unfortunately,several critical elements of the new requirements are vague andsubject to broad agency discretion.andP;  In the event of a violation,the head of the contracting activity may disqualify an offeror;seek to recapture profit on a contract; cancel the procurement; ortake other appropriate action.andP;  Contractors can protect themselvesby briefing appropriate staff on the program then obtaining theirknowledgeable certifications; establishing procurement integritytraining programs; incorporating protective clauses into contractswith third parties; and reviewing current procedures for markingand protecting documents.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government RegulationGovernment ContractsEthicsPurchasing SystemsTrainingPolicy.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The Procurement Integrity Act: a sample poster for contractors.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>